  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support to Livelihood Resilience through CECI</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The production of tubers and ginger represents one of the main economic pillars in the rural areas of Haiti. It represents an integral part of the economic reconstruction and revenue stream of rural households in all of the six communal sections targeted by this program. Despite differences in the agro-ecological characteristics between the North (wet mountain areas) and Northeast (lowland areas), they present relatively similar production potential and constraints. These constraints are characterized by difficulty to access seeds, high cost of agricultural input and labor, inappropriate cultivation practices, and the inherent weakness in packaging, conservation techniques and marketing.  

The project provides technical assistance, resources, strategy and methodologies to support select farmers in the Northern and Northeastern Departments to enhance their livelihood resilience and improve their opportunities for income-generation. It increases the capacity of Communal Agricultural Office (BAC), Haitian Red Cross (HRC) and Rural Producer Organizations to support extension training of farmers in appropriate value chains in target communal sections; increases farmers&apos; resilience through improved knowledge, practices and assets for disaster resistant agriculture techniques (ginger, root crops); and enhances incomes in targeted communities and households - in particular young women - through transformation and commercialization of yam, cassava, sweet potato and/or ginger.</narrative>
  </description>
